{
  "doc_id": "5670",
  "text": "Several NAS-overexpressing plants have been confirmed to tolerate Fe deficiency compared to NT plants [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The plant growth is dramatically reduced under Fe-deficient conditions. The plant heights and soil and plant analyzer development (SPAD) values (which represent the chlorophyll content) of NAS-overexpressing soybean and sweet potato plants were higher than those of NT plants when grown in calcareous soil with low Fe availability, suggesting that these transgenic plants were conferred tolerance to Fe deficiency. Under normal soil conditions, their growth did not differ. In rice plants, the Fe-deficiency tolerance of NAS-overexpressing rice plants in calcareous soil was not determined. HvNAS1-overexpressing rice exhibits enhanced NAS activity in Fe-deficient roots [CITATION_4] and contains a higher amount of NA and deoxymugineic acid than NT plants in both roots and shoots [CITATION_5] . Transgenic rice lines expressing barley NAS genes exhibit increased tolerance to low Fe availability in calcareous soil . Rice plants overexpressing OsIRO2, a transcription factor that enhances expression of Fe deficiency-inducible genes including OsNAS1 and OsNAS2, showed improved tolerance to low Fe availability in calcareous soil [CITATION_6] . These results suggest that overexpression of the NAS gene in rice also enhances tolerance to Fe deficiency.",
